ere. B strong technically but interpersonal issues. Which is more critical? For long-haul, safety and reliability are top, but crew communication also vital. C's egocentric and unwillingness to further education could be problematic for long-term development. But reliability and calmness are high.\n\nWe need to decide. Perhaps we can ask Agent 3 for any additional info about candidate C's crew integration or reliability. But we already have that from Agent 1: positive atmosphere, 100% reliable. That is strong. Agent 3 didn't mention that. So we have new info that C is reliable and creates positive atmosphere. That may outweigh his communication difficulty? He also has difficulty communicating ideas, but positive atmosphere suggests he works well with crew. Could be that he communicates well with crew but not with others? Hard to know.\n\nGiven this, I might shift to Candidate C as best. But need to weigh: C's egocentric and not willing to further education could affect long-term adaptability to new tech/regulations. However long-distance pilot may not need further education as much as staying current. But still important.\n\nWe could ask Agent 3 if they have any info on C's willingness to further education or any mitigation. But we already have that. Maybe ask about D's crew integration? But we have limited.\n\nWe need to produce final vote. I think Candidate C now looks strong: reliability, calm, quick decisions, tech understanding, crew positive atmosphere. The communication difficulty may be mitigated by positive atmosphere. Egocentric may be less critical if he still works well with crew. Not willing to further education is a concern but maybe less immediate.\n\nThus I will vote Candidate C.\n\nNow produce public message summarizing reasoning, referencing new info from Agent 1, and stating vote."}
